==English==
===Alternative spelling===
*[[mareschal]]

===Etymology===
Old French '''mareschal''' (stable officer) < from Frankish ''*marhskalk'' (horse-servant) < Proto-Germanic ''*markhaz'' (horse), possibly from a Gaulish word of unknown origin, + Proto-Germanic ''*skalkaz'' (servant).

===Pronunciation===
*:Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-ɑː(r)ʃəl|-ɑː(r)ʃəl]]

===Noun===
'''marshal'''

# A high-ranking officer in the household of a medieval prince or lord, who was originally in charge of the cavalry and later the military forces in general. 
# A military officer of the highest rank.
# A person in charge of the ceremonial arrangement and management of a gathering.
# A [[sheriff]]'s assistant.
# <!--WTF?--> The highest ranking piece in the board game [[Stratego]].

